        <hl1>Toward Better Care for the Old</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from nursing home administrator Christopher Cherney notes that new California law sets nursing home staffing standards (Aug 7 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Acceptable Nursing Home Care''  (editorial, Aug. 7) suggests that Congress ''wait a year'' before setting staff ratios for nursing homes.</p>
        <p>California is not waiting to set staff ratios. As of April 1, California law required 3.2 hours of direct care per patient per 24-hour day.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Acceptable Nursing Home Care''  (editorial, Aug. 7) suggests that Congress ''wait a year'' before setting staff ratios for nursing homes.</p>
        <p>California is not waiting to set staff ratios. As of April 1, California law required 3.2 hours of direct care per patient per 24-hour day.</p>
        <p>To help pay for California's new staffing standard, the Legislature recently authorized 15 to 20 percent rate increases for Medicaid recipients (68 percent of all California nursing home residents).</p>
        <p>In California, mandated staffing ratios backed by increased government financing will result in higher wages for nurses, more nursing staff and better patient care.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER CHERNEY  Berkeley, Calif., Aug. 7, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a nursing home administrator.</p>
      </block>
